"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2kings-1-3.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/2kings.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/2kings.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/2kings.json (existing ch17 entry)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 1: Baal-zebub of Ekron explained as Philistine healing oracle deity; NT "Beelzebul" connection noted.
  The hairy-man description of Elijah and its connection to John the Baptist's appearance (Matt 3:4).
  The third captain's kneeling as the pattern of prophetic intercession accepted.
- Ch 2: The journey route (Gilgal→Bethel→Jericho→Jordan) as reversal of the conquest entry.
  Elisha's double portion as legal firstborn inheritance (Deut 21:17), not miraculous amplification.
  The sons of the prophets as prophetic guild communities. The "boys" who mock are young men, not
  small children; the mockery is of the prophetic office itself.
- Ch 3: The Mesha stele as archaeological corroboration. The harpist's role in prophetic inspiration.
  The red water/blood illusion as optical phenomenon exploited by YHWH. Mesha's child sacrifice
  and the theologically difficult "great wrath" in v27.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS2 = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Moab's rebellion immediately after Ahab's death (ca. 853 BCE) illustrates the vassal-state dynamics of the ANE: tributary relationships were personal covenants with the suzerain king, and a new king meant renegotiation or revolt. Mesha king of Moab's tribute — a hundred thousand lambs and the wool of a hundred thousand rams (v3:4) — is confirmed by the Mesha stele (the Moabite Stone, discovered 1868), which records Mesha's own account of his rebellion and the wars described in 2 Kings 1 and 3. The stele is one of the earliest extrabiblical inscriptions to mention YHWH by name ('YHWH' appears in Mesha's account of his conquest of Israelite territory).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Baal-zebub ('lord of flies') was the deity of Ekron, a Philistine city approximately 35 miles southwest of Jerusalem. The name is probably a derisive Israelite alteration of Baal-zebul ('lord of the high place' or 'exalted lord') — substituting <em>zebub</em> (flies) for <em>zebul</em> (exalted). The god was associated with healing and oracular consultation; Ahaziah's messengers are sent to ask whether he would recover, a standard ANE practice of divine consultation before prognosis. The NT preserves the altered form 'Beelzebul' (Matt 12:24; Luke 11:15) as the name Jesus's opponents give to the prince of demons — the Philistine deity of Ekron becomes in Jewish tradition a title for the chief of the demonic realm.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Elijah intercepts the messengers on the road. The angel of the LORD directing the prophet to an interception rather than a confrontation at the palace maintains Elijah's distance from the court — the prophet operates outside royal jurisdiction. The question 'Is it because there is no God in Israel that you are going to inquire of Baal-zebub?' is the theological indictment: Israel has a living God who can and does answer such questions (cf. 1 Kgs 18:24). The choice of a foreign healing deity over YHWH is a covenant violation, not merely a religious preference.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The death sentence pronounced before the king ever sees Elijah — delivered through his own messengers — demonstrates prophetic authority that operates independently of royal cooperation. The Deuteronomistic pattern: consult a foreign deity rather than YHWH → death sentence from YHWH's prophet. The king cannot avoid the verdict by avoiding the prophet; the word of YHWH overtakes those who reject it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The messengers' premature return signals the narrative's irony: the man the king sent to learn from Ekron's god has been intercepted by YHWH's prophet before he even reached his destination. The word of YHWH preempts the consultation with Baal-zebub — the false oracle never gets to speak because the true oracle has already spoken.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The messengers report the prophet's challenge verbatim, which is significant: they recognize the authority of the unnamed prophet's question before they know who he is. The prophetic word carries its own credibility — the challenge 'Is it because there is no God in Israel?' is self-evidently correct, which is why the messengers relay it rather than dismiss it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ahaziah's immediate question — 'What sort of man was it?' — reflects the ANE practice of identifying prophets by their distinctive appearance and associated deity. Prophets often had identifying marks: Zechariah 13:4 mentions the 'hairy garment' (<em>adderet se'ar</em>) as prophetic attire. The king recognizes Elijah from the description alone, without needing to be told his name.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The description — 'a hairy man with a leather belt around his waist' — is Elijah's identifying profile in Israel. The hairy garment and leather belt are marks of an ascetic prophetic lifestyle: outside royal patronage, living in the wilderness, wearing the rough clothing of one who survives without the court's provision. John the Baptist adopts precisely this profile (Matt 3:4: 'Now John wore a garment of camel's hair and a leather belt around his waist'), consciously embodying the Elijah tradition in preparation for his role as Elijah-figure before Christ (Mal 4:5; Matt 11:14; Luke 1:17).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Man of God' (<em>ish ha-elohim</em>) is the standing honorific for a prophet in 1-2 Kings; it acknowledges divine authorization and prophetic authority. The captain's command — 'Come down!' — treats Elijah as a royal subject. Elijah's position 'on the top of a hill' mirrors the prophetic practice of high-place prayer (like Elisha on Carmel, 2 Kgs 4:25), but here the elevated position is also the terrain of prophetic authority: he summons fire from above.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Fire from heaven consuming soldiers is a rare prophetic act — the most famous precedent is the fire at Carmel (1 Kgs 18:38). The fire here is judicial: it is the verdict on unlawful use of royal military authority against a prophet. The fifty soldiers represent the king; Elijah's fire is the prophetic counter-authority that the king cannot override with soldiers. Jesus's disciples asking to 'call fire down from heaven' on an inhospitable Samaritan village (Luke 9:54) explicitly evokes this Elijah precedent; Jesus rebukes them, signaling that the ministry of the Son of Man is not fire-and-judgment but saving the lost (Luke 9:55-56).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A second company of fifty sent after the first group's destruction demonstrates the king's refusal to receive the message. The repetition is a narrative pattern of warning: three increasingly urgent confrontations (the messengers, the first fifty, the second fifty) before the final meeting. This pattern of escalating divine warning before judgment recurs in the prophetic literature (Amos 4:6-11: 'yet you did not return to me').</p>",
    "12": "<p>The second fire consuming the second fifty reinforces the prophetic verdict without escalating the content: Elijah does not add to the message, only repeats it. The repetition of the fire judgment is not cruelty but judicial consistency — the king's messengers are agents of the king's rejection of YHWH's word, and the judgment falls on them accordingly.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The third captain's kneeling and plea for mercy is the narrative turning point. Unlike his predecessors who commanded, this captain petitions: 'Let my life be precious in your eyes.' This is the posture of supplication rather than coercion. The ANE honor-shame dynamic is operative: by prostrating himself and begging, the captain is choosing prophetic authority over royal authority — a socially costly act. Elijah responds to genuine submission; his fire was never for killing but for establishing prophetic immunity from royal coercion.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The captain's reference to the two previous groups' deaths as grounds for his plea is unusual: he is arguing from the established pattern of divine judgment to obtain mercy for himself. This is the logic of the penitential psalms: 'YHWH acts this way; I therefore throw myself on your mercy.' The angel of the LORD's instruction to go with him confirms that the fire was never personal — it was judicial, and ceases when the appropriate response is given.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The angel of the LORD instructs Elijah to go with the third captain — not because the captain deserves it more than his predecessors, but because his posture was different. The same prophetic message is now delivered directly to the king's face. The progression (fire from a distance → direct confrontation) mirrors the prophetic escalation in other narratives: YHWH speaks at a distance until the situation requires direct confrontation.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Elijah delivers the death oracle directly to Ahaziah in the palace: the prophet who was summoned by royal soldiers ends up face-to-face with the king, delivering the same verdict the king tried to avoid by sending to Ekron. The rhetorical irony is complete: the journey to Baal-zebub was meant to get a healing word; the word Ahaziah receives instead is death, from YHWH's prophet. The reason is explicit — 'because you sent messengers to inquire of Baal-zebub as though there were no God in Israel.'</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ahaziah dies 'according to the word of the LORD that Elijah had spoken' — the Deuteronomistic formula confirming the reliability of the prophetic word. The king who rejected YHWH's oracle and sought a Philistine deity's word dies exactly as YHWH's prophet said. Jehoram succeeds him in the second year of Jehoram son of Jehoshaphat of Judah — the dual dating system (synchronizing Israelite and Judahite regnal years) is the Deuteronomistic historian's method for maintaining a synchronized chronology of the two kingdoms throughout 1-2 Kings.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The standard closing formula — 'The rest of the acts of Ahaziah... are they not written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?' — refers not to the biblical book of Chronicles but to a now-lost court record kept in the Israelite royal archive. This formula appears after nearly every king in 1-2 Kings, confirming that the Deuteronomistic historian worked from official annalistic sources. Ahaziah's reign is the shortest on record — just two years — and his primary act is his rejection of YHWH in favor of Baal-zebub.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>The geography of Elijah's final journey reverses the conquest route: Gilgal was the first camp after crossing the Jordan under Joshua; Bethel was the site of Jeroboam's golden calves and a longstanding sanctuary; Jericho was Israel's first conquest; the Jordan is the entry point into the land. Elijah moves backward through the land's sacred history toward the Jordan, as if retreating from Israel's settled existence toward the threshold wilderness. The prophetic transition mirrors the entry: what Moses began (Joshua crossing the Jordan) Elijah reverses as he prepares to leave the land for heaven.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Elijah's three attempts to leave Elisha behind ('stay here, for the LORD has sent me to Bethel/Jericho/the Jordan') are ritual tests of Elisha's commitment to the succession. Elisha's threefold refusal ('as the LORD lives, and as you yourself live, I will not leave you') echoes Ruth's threefold commitment to Naomi (Ruth 1:16-17) — the binding formula in both cases signals a covenant-level loyalty that cannot be broken by the superior's release. Elisha's persistence is a claim on the prophetic succession, not mere personal loyalty.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The 'sons of the prophets' (<em>bene ha-nebi'im</em>) at Bethel and Jericho are prophetic guilds — communities of prophets associated with particular sanctuaries. Their existence shows that prophecy in Israel was not purely charismatic and solitary (though Elijah functioned that way) but also institutional, with training communities. These guilds appear throughout 2 Kings associated with Elisha's ministry. Their foreknowledge of Elijah's departure ('Do you know that today the LORD is going to take your master from you?') indicates that the prophetic community had received a revelation about this event that Elisha has also received — both know, but Elisha keeps silent.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The repetition at Jericho follows the same pattern as Bethel: Elijah releases Elisha; Elisha refuses. The sons of the prophets at Jericho repeat the same question as those at Bethel. The threefold pattern (Bethel, Jericho, Jordan) is a literary device signaling completeness and transition — the same structure used for three-day waiting periods, three-fold temptations, and Peter's three denials. The pattern's repetition emphasizes Elisha's determination over the sons of the prophets' tentative awareness.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Elisha's response to the sons of the prophets at Jericho — 'Yes, I know. Be silent' — is theologically significant: he knows and has accepted what is coming. The command to be silent may reflect a mourning protocol (the prophetic community knows but the moment has not yet come to speak) or may indicate that Elisha does not want the emotional weight of communal grief to distract from his focused attention on Elijah's final moments — for seeing Elijah taken is the condition of receiving the double portion (v10).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Jordan is the final sacred threshold: the boundary between the land of promise and the wilderness/Transjordan. Elijah and Elisha cross the Jordan together, recreating the entry into the land (Joshua 3-4) in reverse. The fifty prophets who stand watching at a distance represent the prophetic community as witnesses, but only Elisha crosses with Elijah — the successor alone goes to the threshold.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The fifty sons of the prophets who watch from a distance are the witnesses who will confirm the transfer of the spirit (v15: 'The spirit of Elijah rests on Elisha'). The concentric structure — Elisha alone with Elijah at the Jordan's edge, the fifty at a distance — mirrors the Sinai pattern: Moses alone at the summit, elders partway up, people at the base (Exod 24:1-2). In both cases, the innermost position is where the decisive transfer or covenant occurs.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elijah's rolling up his cloak and striking the water — parting it so they cross on dry ground — explicitly recreates the exodus sea crossing (Exod 14:21-22) and the Jordan crossing under Joshua (Josh 3:14-17). The cloak is the symbol of prophetic authority: wearing it was Elisha's original commissioning (1 Kgs 19:19-21). Now Elijah uses it for a miracle, and Elisha will use it for the same miracle in v14 as his first act as Elijah's successor. The parting of the Jordan is the sign that Elijah's authority is transferable.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Elisha's request for 'a double portion of your spirit' uses the legal language of firstborn inheritance (Deut 21:17: the firstborn son receives a double portion — <em>pi shnayim</em> — of the estate). He is claiming the position of primary heir in the prophetic succession, not asking for twice as much miraculous power. This is confirmed by the tradition that Elisha performs 16 miracles in Kings versus Elijah's 8 — exactly double. The request defines Elisha as Elijah's prophetic son and heir, the one who carries forward the ministry.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Elijah's condition — 'if you see me as I am taken from you, it will be granted' — connects the gift of the spirit to the act of witnessing. This is a test of prophetic attentiveness: the spirit is given to the one who watches to the end, who keeps his eyes on the departing prophet rather than turning away at the difficulty of the moment. The condition also ensures that no one else can claim the succession based on secondhand knowledge — only Elisha sees the whirlwind, and only Elisha receives the double portion.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The chariot of fire and horses of fire are theophanic imagery — YHWH's heavenly military escort (see also 2 Kgs 6:17, where Elisha's servant sees the mountains full of horses and chariots of fire). The whirlwind (<em>seara</em>) that takes Elijah is the same element that appears in the YHWH speeches in Job (38:1; 40:6) and in Ezekiel's throne-chariot vision (Ezek 1:4). The fiery chariot separates Elijah and Elisha at the moment of ascension — the divine escort comes between them, and Elijah is taken up. Elijah is one of only two people in the OT taken without dying (Enoch, Gen 5:24), which makes him a persistent eschatological figure.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Elisha's cry — 'My father, my father! The chariot of Israel and its horsemen!' — is a formal mourning formula combined with a military-theological title. 'My father, my father!' is the mourning cry of a son losing a parent (2 Sam 18:33 follows the same pattern with different content). 'The chariot of Israel and its horsemen' is a title acknowledging that Elijah himself was Israel's true military defense — not the king's army, but the prophet who stood between Israel and divine judgment. Elisha tears his own clothes in mourning, a standard ANE grief ritual, signaling the end of the succession period and the beginning of his own ministry.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elisha picks up Elijah's fallen cloak, the symbol of prophetic authority. The cloak's transfer completes the succession that began when Elijah threw it over Elisha at Horeb (1 Kgs 19:19). The fallen cloak is Elijah's last gift to his successor — not an intentional throwing but a natural consequence of the ascension, received as inheritance. Elisha returns to the Jordan bank to perform his first miracle with the cloak, establishing immediately that the transfer of authority is complete.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Elisha strikes the water with Elijah's cloak and asks 'Where is the LORD, the God of Elijah?' — not doubting YHWH's presence but invoking it, recalling what YHWH did through Elijah and claiming the same authority for the new prophetic ministry. The water parts. The first miracle of Elisha's independent ministry recreates Elijah's last miracle (v8), confirming before the fifty witnesses that the spirit has transferred. The sons of the prophets watching from the shore will observe the parting and draw the conclusion stated in v15.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'The spirit of Elijah rests on Elisha' — the fifty sons of the prophets recognize the transferred spirit by the miracle they witnessed. The Elijah-spirit language anticipates the NT description of John the Baptist coming 'in the spirit and power of Elijah' (Luke 1:17) and the Holy Spirit's descent on the disciples at Pentecost as a corporate Elisha-succession: the disciples receive the spirit of the one who ascended (Acts 2:33) and perform miracles in his name as Elisha performs them in YHWH's name.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The sons of the prophets' proposal to search for Elijah reflects their uncertainty about the nature of his departure: they know he was taken but do not yet understand that 'taken by a whirlwind' means permanently gone, not temporarily transported (as the Spirit had previously transported Elijah to various places, 1 Kgs 18:12). Their framework for prophetic transportation doesn't include permanent heavenly ascension — this is a novel category. Elisha's refusal shows that he witnessed the ascension and understands what the others do not.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Elisha's reluctant concession — pressing until he was embarrassed — is a realistic pastoral detail. The communal pressure on a new leader to defer to the group's anxiety is familiar in any tradition of succession. Elisha knows the search will fail, but allows it to proceed so the community will arrive at certainty through their own experience rather than his testimony alone. The three-day failed search becomes their experiential confirmation that Elijah is truly gone.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Did I not tell you not to go?' — Elisha's mild rebuke is the new prophet establishing his authority through verified knowledge. His certainty about Elijah's departure was prophetically founded; the sons of the prophets' uncertainty was spiritually unfounded. The interaction positions Elisha as the source of reliable knowledge about divine action — a fundamental role of the prophet in Israel.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The transition from the Elijah succession narrative to Elisha's first healing miracle (the Jericho spring) is abrupt — suggesting the compiler is demonstrating the range of the new prophet's ministry immediately. Jericho's 'bad water' is historically problematic, since Jericho is known for springs; the complaint may reflect a specific spring that went brackish, or the narrative may be etiological, explaining how a specific spring received its good quality.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A new bowl and salt — the healing elements are significant: salt in ANE culture was associated with covenants (Lev 2:13: 'season all your grain offerings with salt'), with preservation and purification, and with hospitality. The 'new bowl' for the salt suggests that the healing agent must be uncorrupted and freshly prepared — a ritual purity requirement for the prophetic act. Elisha throws the salt directly into the spring; the healing is enacted through a material medium, a pattern consistent with prophetic symbolism throughout 1-2 Kings and carried into the NT (Jesus uses mud, spit, touch).</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Thus says the LORD: I have healed this water' — the healing of the spring is YHWH's act through Elisha's medium, not a magical property of salt. The 'I have healed' formula establishes divine authority behind the act. Springs and water sources were often sites of religious significance in the ANE; by healing Jericho's spring, Elisha establishes prophetic authority over a city associated with the curse from Joshua (Josh 6:26) and now reclaimed for blessing. The water 'has been wholesome to this day' (v22) is the etiological marker that places this event as the explanation for Jericho's historically good springs.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The fulfillment notice — 'to this day, according to the word Elisha spoke' — is the Deuteronomistic formula confirming prophetic reliability. The same formula is used throughout Kings to confirm that prophetic words were historically verified. The formula assumes a later reader who can observe the ongoing effect, suggesting these etiological notices were preserved from the original compiler's time.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The 'small boys' (<em>ne'arim qetannim</em>) at Bethel who taunt Elisha are likely young men — teenagers or older — not small children. The taunt 'Go up, baldy! Go up, baldy!' has two layers: the shaved head may mock a distinctive hairstyle or lack thereof (some scholars suggest prophets had distinctive hairstyles, and the taunt mocks the absence of Elijah's hairy appearance); and 'go up' (<em>ale</em>) may mockingly echo Elijah's 'going up' (<em>alah</em>) in the whirlwind — essentially 'disappear like Elijah did.' The taunt is not merely rude; it is a public rejection of prophetic authority in Bethel, the site of Jeroboam's golden calves and a center of official apostasy.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The curse on the mockers and the subsequent death of forty-two of them by bears is one of the most theologically troubling passages in Kings. The commentator's restraint here is appropriate: the text does not editorialize; the events speak. The Bethel context matters: this is the city of Jeroboam's golden calves, Israel's official apostasy. The rejection of Elisha's prophetic authority in this city is a covenant violation, not mere rudeness. The bears are the instrument of YHWH's judgment on a community that rejects his prophet — a judgment foreshadowed in the covenant curses (Lev 26:22: 'I will send wild animals against you').</p>",
    "25": "<p>Elisha moves to Mount Carmel — the site of Elijah's great victory over the Baal prophets (1 Kgs 18) — and then returns to Samaria, the Israelite capital. The itinerary establishes his authority across the prophetic landscape: Jericho (healed), Bethel (judged), Carmel (visited), Samaria (based). Elisha's ministry will center on the northern kingdom and its capital, in contrast to Elijah's more itinerant and confrontational presence. The Elisha narrative that follows will demonstrate both continuity (Elijah's spirit and authority) and difference (Elisha is more accessible, works more miracles, and engages more constructively with kings).</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>Jehoram son of Ahab rules Israel from ca. 852–841 BCE. The synchronization with Jehoshaphat's eighteenth year connects the northern and southern royal chronologies — the Deuteronomistic historian's method throughout 1-2 Kings. Jehoram is Ahab's second son to reign (Ahaziah died without an heir); the dynasty of Omri thus continues, though now in its declining phase. The parallel account in 2 Chronicles 18-21 provides additional context for Jehoshaphat's reign as the politically dominant figure in this episode.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jehoram receives a partial approval — 'not like his father and mother' — because he removes the sacred pillar (<em>matsevah</em>) of Baal that Ahab erected. The matsevah (standing stone) was the standard cultic symbol for Baal worship; its removal shows at least cosmetic covenant loyalty. But the qualification 'nevertheless he clung to the sins of Jeroboam' refers to Jeroboam's golden calves at Bethel and Dan — the founding sin of the northern kingdom that every northern king perpetuates. The Deuteronomistic judgment system distinguishes between the worse (Baal/Asherah imports) and the foundational (Jeroboam's structural apostasy).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The 'sins of Jeroboam' is the Deuteronomistic catchphrase for the golden calves at Bethel and Dan — worship of YHWH through calf-images in unauthorized sanctuaries outside Jerusalem. Jeroboam established this as a political-religious alternative to pilgrimage to Jerusalem (1 Kgs 12:28-29), citing Aaron's words at Sinai ('these are your gods, O Israel'), which made it a form of syncretism that persisted through every northern king's reign. The sin was structural: built into the northern state religion from its founding, perpetuated by every subsequent king until the Assyrian exile.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Mesha king of Moab is the most historically documented figure in this passage outside the Bible. The Mesha stele (ca. 840 BCE), found at Dibon (biblical Dibon-gad), is written in Moabite — closely related to Hebrew — and records Mesha's perspective on the same events. Mesha describes paying tribute to 'the house of Omri' (the dynasty name for Israel) and then his rebellion after Ahab's death, consistent with 2 Kings 1:1 and 3:5. The stele mentions YHWH by name and describes Mesha taking 'the vessels of YHWH' from the Israelite town of Nebo — one of the earliest extrabiblical references to YHWH. The hundred thousand lambs and the wool of a hundred thousand rams represents a massive agricultural tribute, consistent with Moab's known sheep-farming economy.</p>",
    "5": "<p>After Ahab's death, Moab's rebellion follows the standard ANE pattern: a new king's accession is the optimal moment for vassal revolt. The tribute relationship was personal between Ahab and Mesha; without the strong suzerain king, the relationship collapses. The exact timing — 'after Ahab died' — suggests Mesha waited for the political transition rather than rebelling during Ahab's militarily strong reign.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jehoram musters 'all Israel' — the standing army of the northern kingdom — to suppress the Moabite revolt. This is a standard Deuteronomistic summary of royal military mobilization. The campaign's political structure (three kings, v7) reflects the complex suzerain-vassal relationships of the region: Judah under Jehoshaphat and Edom (as Judah's vassal) are brought into what began as Israel's domestic suppression of a tributary.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jehoram's appeal to Jehoshaphat — 'Will you go with me to fight against Moab?' — follows the precedent of 1 Kings 22:4, where Ahab made the same appeal to Jehoshaphat for the Ramoth-gilead campaign. Jehoshaphat's consistent response ('I am as you are, my people as your people, my horses as your horses') in both cases signals the political and dynastic alignment between northern and southern kingdoms during this period, cemented by the marriage of Jehoshaphat's son Jehoram to Ahab's daughter Athaliah (2 Kgs 8:16-18). Jehoshaphat's diplomatic language is formulaic rather than enthusiastic.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The southern route through the wilderness of Edom is strategically significant: attacking from the south would surprise the Moabites, who would expect an assault from the north across the Arnon River. The route required traversing approximately 150 miles of difficult terrain through the Negev and Edom — a seven-day march (v9). Edom's participation as the third kingdom is explained by its vassal status under Jehoshaphat (1 Kgs 22:47: Edom had no king; the 'king of Edom' here is likely a deputized governor). The coalition of three kings from three compass directions (north, south, east) frames the campaign as a comprehensive effort.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The water crisis after seven days of march — 'there was no water for the army or for the animals that followed them' — is a practical military problem of desert logistics. Seven days through the Negev and Edom without adequate water supply for three armies plus their livestock would be catastrophic. The crisis sets up the need for prophetic intervention: military planning has failed, and only YHWH can supply water in the desert, as he did for Israel in the wilderness (Exod 17:1-7; Num 20:2-13). The situation deliberately echoes the wilderness narratives.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jehoram's lament — 'The LORD has called these three kings together only to hand them over to Moab' — reflects the Deuteronomistic narrative's consistent portrait of Jehoram as the Ahab heir who interprets events through the lens of divine hostility to the house of Omri. His theological reading is partially correct (YHWH's judgment on Israel is a consistent theme) but lacks the faith to respond with prayer. The theological despair of the apostate king contrasts with Jehoshaphat's instinct to seek a prophet.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jehoshaphat's question — 'Is there no prophet of the LORD here?' — reflects the political-theological significance of prophetic consultation in the ANE. Before major military campaigns, kings consulted prophets (or other diviners). Jehoshaphat's insistence on a prophet of YHWH (as distinct from royal prophets or Baal prophets) is his consistent contribution throughout 1-2 Kings: he provides the legitimating prophetic consultation that the northern kings cannot or will not seek from YHWH. The servant's knowledge that Elisha 'used to pour water on the hands of Elijah' identifies Elisha by his role as Elijah's personal attendant — a detail that marks him as the authenticated successor.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jehoshaphat's response — 'The word of the LORD is with him' — accepts Elisha's Elijanic credentials. The three kings going down to visit the prophet is a reversal of royal protocol: normally prophets came to kings; here kings descend to the prophet. The spatial movement (kings descend) is a social inversion signaling prophetic authority over royal power, consistent with the Elijah-Ahab encounters in 1 Kings.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elisha's initial rebuff of Jehoram — 'Go to the prophets of your father and your mother' — echoes Elijah's relationship with Ahab: the true prophet of YHWH has no natural relationship with the apostate northern king. Elisha explicitly distances himself from patronage by the house of Omri. The rebuff is also a diagnostic: Jehoram's response ('No, it is the LORD who has called these three kings together to hand them over to Moab') shows at least some theological awareness, however despairing.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Elisha's only concession to Jehoram's presence is his respect for Jehoshaphat: 'Were it not for my regard for Jehoshaphat king of Judah, I would not look at you or see you.' Jehoshaphat's presence is what secures prophetic consultation for the campaign — without the Judahite king's YHWH-fearing reputation, Elisha would refuse the northern king entirely. This narrative subtly advances the Deuteronomistic argument that Judah's relative fidelity to YHWH (even Jehoshaphat's partial obedience) provides the access to divine resources that the northern kingdom cannot obtain on its own terms.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Now bring me a harpist.' Music as a medium for prophetic inspiration appears in 1 Samuel 10:5 (the band of prophets with musical instruments) and is implied in the psalmic tradition. The connection between music and prophetic Spirit in the ANE reflects the understanding that altered states of consciousness facilitated divine communication — an understanding shared across many ancient cultures but channeled in Israel through legitimate prophetic figures under YHWH's authority. The harpist's playing calms Elisha's spirit enough to receive and deliver YHWH's word — not a trance state but a focused receptivity.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Make this valley full of trenches' (<em>gebaim gebaim</em>) — the command to dig trenches or cisterns in the dry valley floor is the mechanism for collecting the water YHWH will provide. The army must act in faith before the water arrives: the trenches are dug in a valley with no rain, no visible source of water, in a desert region. The principle is consistent across miracle narratives: faith acts before the provision arrives (cf. the widow's oil, 2 Kgs 4:3-4; the five loaves, Mark 6:38-41).</p>",
    "17": "<p>'You will see no wind or rain, yet that valley will be filled with water.' YHWH provides water through neither of the natural mechanisms (wind-driven rain, direct rainfall) but through a source hidden from view. The water flows from Edom — likely from flash floods caused by distant rain in the Edomite mountains that the army never sees. The miraculous element is not the absence of natural causation but the precise timing, direction, and sufficiency of the supply in response to prophetic word. This is the biblical pattern: YHWH works through natural means timed and directed by his word.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'This is a small thing in the sight of the LORD.' The water supply — what the army considered an impossible crisis — is described as a minor divine act compared to what follows. The rhetorical move establishes YHWH's unlimited capacity: if the impossible (water in the desert) is small, then the military victory is equally available. The comparison also implicitly addresses Israel's fear: the god who provided water for Israel in the wilderness (Exod 17; Num 20) is the same god now providing it in this desert.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The scale of the commanded devastation — 'every fortified city, every important town, fell every good tree, stop up every spring, ruin every good piece of land with stones' — exceeds standard ANE military practice. Ancient Near Eastern law codes and even Mosaic law (Deut 20:19-20) typically protected orchards and trees from warfare destruction. The severity here is unique to this campaign and relates to Moab's theological status as a nation with whom Israel has a complex covenant history (Balaam, Ruth) but also persistent hostility (Num 25; Judg 3:12-30).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The water arrives 'at the time of the morning offering' — the daily temple sacrifice in Jerusalem (Exod 29:38-42), here providing the precise chronological marker: the miracle of water occurred simultaneously with the morning sacrifice at the temple. The timing is probably coincidental in the narrative's original form but is theologically significant for the compiler: YHWH's provision in the field is synchronized with his worship in the sanctuary, suggesting that the two are not separate but related. The water comes 'from the direction of Edom' — the distant mountains, as described in v17.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Moabite military response — 'every man who could bear arms, from the youngest to the oldest' — is a total mobilization, a sign of existential threat. The coalition of three kings threatening from the south was unexpected (Moab would have guarded the northern Arnon crossing); the southern approach required a total mobilization from existing positions. The Moabites are moving to meet the threat at the border of Edom rather than defending deeper in their territory.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The water's red color in the morning sun — 'red as blood' — is the optical illusion that becomes YHWH's tactical weapon. Water reflecting the red Edomite soil, or the red morning light itself, created a blood-like appearance. The Moabites' interpretation — 'the kings must have fought each other' — reflects military intelligence gathered from the broken coalition: three kings with potentially conflicting interests, a desperate water crisis. Their plausible inference triggers their own defeat. YHWH uses Moab's rational military reasoning against them.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'This is blood! The kings must have fought each other and killed one another.' The Moabite interpretation is militarily coherent: three-king coalitions were notoriously unstable in the ANE, and the water crisis (if known to Moabite intelligence) would have made internal conflict seem inevitable. Their confident advance to plunder, however, turns an apparently certain victory into a rout. This pattern — the enemy's confidence becomes the mechanism of their defeat — recurs throughout the exodus narrative (Exod 14:25) and prophetic literature.</p>",
    "24": "<p>When the Israelites 'rose up and attacked,' the Moabites fled — the reversal of the expected outcome. The campaign's military success is total; the subsequent devastation (v25) is systematic. The word used for the Israelite counter-attack suggests a rapid, unexpected response: they were waiting for the Moabites to enter the camp, then struck. The strategic trap (appearing defeated/absent while the Moabites advanced) may have been deliberate or providential.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The systematic devastation of Moabite territory — felling trees, stopping springs, covering good land with stones — was military punishment of a tributary that violated its vassal covenant. Such destructive tactics were common in ANE warfare as deterrents to future rebellion. The specific mention of each type of destruction (cities, trees, springs, land) reflects the Deuteronomistic listing style that catalogs covenant-curse fulfillment (Deut 28:18, 40). The siege of Kir-hareseth (the Moabite capital) is the campaign's military climax.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Mesha's attempted breakout toward the king of Edom (the weakest member of the coalition) with seven hundred swordsmen is a last desperate military gambit. The choice of Edom rather than Israel or Judah reflects tactical calculation: Edom as a vassal state was the most recently subordinated and potentially the most internally unstable coalition partner. The attempt fails — Edom holds — and the coalition maintains the siege. Mesha is cornered within Kir-hareseth with no military options left.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The most theologically difficult verse in the chapter: Mesha takes his firstborn son 'who was to succeed him' and offers him as a burnt offering on the city wall. Human sacrifice — specifically child sacrifice — was practiced in the ANE as a last resort under siege, appealing to the national deity (in Moab's case, Chemosh) for intervention. 'Great wrath came upon Israel' — the Hebrew <em>qetseph gadol</em> could mean either divine wrath (YHWH's, or Chemosh's?) or human rage and horror (the Israelite army's revulsion at the sight). Commentators are divided: some argue Chemosh responded to Mesha's sacrifice and drove Israel away; others that Israel withdrew in horror or that YHWH's judgment came on Israel for conducting a campaign that had violated the terms of holy war. The text refuses to resolve the ambiguity — the Israelites withdrew and returned to their own land, leaving Mesha's child sacrifice as the narrative's dark final image.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '2kings')
    merge_comm(existing, KINGS2)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2kings', existing)
    print('2 Kings 1–3 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
